column263: i didnt see the point in getting anything less that 10 dollars so i invested in A most of the time. when it reached a value that i was satisfied with  i would try to maintain that value. i understood all the intructions.

I started out at 50% and then I kept it around 20% for the next rounds. Depending on what the previous rate was I made a judgement call. If it was low before around .6 then I'd choose to keep my A asset % low; if ithe % was high then I chose my A asset to be around 25%.
I went about making my investment decisions by being cautious about the changes in the return percentage. I took risks in the necessary situations. The experiment was very clear.

I had a few different strategies |  | a) a set portfolio % for entirety of the periods (I tried this several times with percentages ranging from 50/50 to 80/20 (bonds/stocks) |  | b) varying percentages thru the periods (I started agressively and trended towards a safer portfolio)

I decided to begin by taking a chance to increase the risk. From there I decided what my desire pay out was and proceeded to attain that. Once I hit my desired payout  I gambled with the rest using a new safety net each time that I prospered so that I would only go up. In some occassions when I fell short I decided to gamble it all.

Pissed me off  especially that one of the randomly chosen payouts had to be my worst performing periods  which was I think $.25 or $35 cents  of ALL periods?? Bad luck. Other than that  I played a conservative strategy as the experiment progressed as I wanted to diversify as much as possible. I only pivoted towards this strategy when I found out how the scenario worked for this experiment. I barely touched the 4%-to-get-$20 button  especially at low amounts of money because it had such a low expected value of winning. Basically  it was like the lottery in which I felt there really was a negative expected payout (but I didn't have time or reason to really calculate it out). But when I had a lot of money (like above $25)  it was safe for me to take that risky investment for just a $1. Still  I received no money from option C.
My method was to invest a great portion of my money at lower quantities and attempt to maintain as much of the money as possible at higher quantities.
This experiment was a little confusing. I allocated more money to an asset depending on how high the multipier was. If asset A had a higher number than B  I gave more money to asset A.

I made my investment decisions based on the multiplier for asset A. If the multiplier seems like it's going up  the I'd put in a higher percentage of investment into asset A. Also if I currently have a larger sum of money than the $3.00 I began with  then I would be investing a higher percentage in asset A simply because I have more money to "manipulate" with. I only bought asset C a few times just to see what the chances are. But since there was only a 4% of getting $20 in return  I didn't want to try it. |  | I believe I generally understood the experiment.
Random investment decisions. There wasn't a pattern I followed since the multipliers for both assets seemed to be really random.
